</div><div class="flex-col gap-1 md:gap-3"><div class="flex flex-grow flex-col max-w-full"><div data-message-author-role="assistant" data-message-id="467ef1d5-6b32-46bf-8efa-587c6683c1ac" class="min-h-[20px] text-message flex flex-col items-start gap-3 whitespace-pre-wrap break-words [.text-message+&amp;]:mt-5 overflow-x-auto"><div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert light"><p>In the context of Petri nets, "concurrent transitions" refer to the ability of multiple transitions to occur at the same time, independent of each other, as long as they have the necessary tokens available in their input places. This concept is a key part of modeling parallel processes or asynchronous events in Petri nets.
</p><p>In your <code>Memo
</code> class, if we continue with the analogy where subscribers are akin to arcs or transitions in Petri nets, then "concurrent transitions" could be thought of as multiple subscribers (or the actions triggered by these subscribers) being activated simultaneously or independently. This would happen if multiple keys in your <code>Memo
</code> class have their values changed around the same time, leading to the simultaneous triggering of their respective subscribers' actions.
</p><p>However, there are some nuances to consider:
</p><ol><li><p><strong>Asynchronous Nature
</strong>: The <code>Memo
</code> class deals with asynchronous operations, which means that the actions triggered by changes in values (akin to transitions in Petri nets) are not necessarily happening simultaneously in the strictest sense, but rather independently and potentially overlapping in time.
</p>
</li><li><p><strong>Event-Driven
</strong>: The <code>Memo
</code> class is event-driven, where changes in state (value updates) trigger actions. This is similar to how transitions in Petri nets are triggered by the availability of tokens.
</p>
</li><li><p><strong>Concurrency Management
</strong>: In Petri nets, the management of concurrency is inherent to the model, with clear rules about how tokens are consumed and produced by transitions. In the <code>Memo
</code> class, while there is an aspect of managing concurrency (especially in how promises are resolved and how subscribers are notified), it doesn't explicitly model concurrency control as in Petri nets.
</p>
</li>
</ol><p>In summary, while there is a conceptual similarity in handling multiple, independent operations (akin to concurrent transitions in Petri nets), the <code>Memo
</code> class's approach to handling these operations is specific to its domain of asynchronous programming and event-driven architecture, rather than the more abstract and generalized concurrency model of Petri nets.
</p>
