</p><p>Regarding the aspect of the <code>Memo
</code> class and its relation to Petri nets, you've highlighted a key point: the ability of a Petri net to trigger transitions only when all required inputs (tokens in all input places) are present. This is a fundamental feature of Petri nets that allows for sophisticated modeling of concurrent systems, ensuring that certain actions only occur when all necessary conditions are met.
</p><p>In the <code>Memo
</code> class, as it currently stands, the subscription mechanism (as implemented in the <code>notifyMe
</code> method) is designed to react to changes in individual keys. It doesn't inherently support the concept of waiting for multiple keys to change before triggering an action. To align more closely with the Petri net model, you would need to implement additional logic that can:
</p><ol><li><strong>Monitor Multiple Keys
</strong>: Create a mechanism where a subscriber can listen to changes in multiple keys simultaneously.
</li><li><strong>Conditional Triggering
</strong>: Ensure that the subscriber's action is only triggered when all the specified keys have changed, or when they meet certain predefined conditions.
</li>
</ol><p>This could be achieved by extending the <code>waitFor
</code> method or creating a new method that allows a subscriber to specify multiple keys and a callback that is only invoked when all those keys have experienced a change. This would bring the <code>Memo
</code> class's functionality closer to the concept of transitions in Petri nets, where a transition fires only when all its input conditions are satisfied.
</p><p>Implementing such a feature would enhance the <code>Memo
</code> class's ability to handle more complex synchronization scenarios, akin to the concurrent and conditional operations modeled by Petri nets.
</p>
